in an emergency call , Professor admits he shot his girlfriend
in an emergency call , Professor Shannon Lamb told police with a slightly treacherous voice that he shot his girlfriend and that officers would have to come to his house .
Lamb was important to stress that his &quot; sweet dog &quot; was still living and probably excited , and he said the dead woman &apos;s family contacts could be found on the phone .
inside the house , officials found the corpse of Amy Prentiss and a hand @-@ written note that had been cracked on a white block : &quot; I &apos;m so sorry , I wanted to , I could undo it , I loved Amy and she is the only woman who ever loved me , &quot; according to the authorities in the letter he signed .
there was no indication that Lamb , who taught in two online courses for Delta State University in Cleveland , Mississippi , had already travelled 300 miles to the school grounds where he shot and killed a popular history professor , Ethan Schmidt , at the door to his office , according to police .
Delta State University police chief Lynn Buford said university staff heard the shooting at 10 : 18 a.m.
he said Lamb made the fatal emergency call sometime after that .
by the end of the day there was another death : lamb took life when police boarded him .
a day after the shootings in the university that forced students and faculty to hide behind closed doors , authorities are still trying to get a picture of what Lamb motivated .
the details released by investigators at both ends of the state , as well as what students and staff who knew him , helped draw a picture of a talented but possibly difficult teacher .
students said they were looking forward to his lessons .
police in Gautier , where Prentiss died , said he has no history of violence or criminal prehistory .
Schmidt himself had mentioned Lamb in a book he wrote in which he mentioned the &quot; wonderful people &quot; with whom he shared his academic life .
both taught in the Department of Social Sciences and History , whose teachers include 17 members , and many students attended courses from both .
at the same time , there were some inclinations to problematic behavior .
one student , Brandon Beavers , who praised Lamb , said he also seemed a little excited and nervous &quot; as if something was wrong with him . &quot;
another student , Mikel Sykes , said Lamm told him he had to deal with stress at the end of the 2014 @-@ 15 academic year .
Lamb had previously asked Delta State University for an assessment on health grounds , saying he had any health problem .
this year , he taught only two online courses .
recent changes in the university &apos;s employment policy meant that the promotion , for which Lamb had worked so hard , would not provide him with a guarantee of an automatic path to an appointment as assistant professor .
University President William LaForge said he knew nothing about a conflict between Lamb and Schmidt , but &quot; of course there was something in Mr. Lambs &apos;s imagination . &quot;
these are questions Lamb can no longer answer .
after fleeing campus , police later found Lambs lane when he returned to Mississippi from Arkansas .
before he could be arrested , Lamb killed himself with a .38 caliber gun in the backyard of a house about a mile south of his parents &apos; house on the outskirts of Greenville , Mississippi , Washington County Coroner Methel Johnson said .
his car was still running in the driveway .
it was not immediately clear why Lamm went to this house , but Johnson said she believes he knew the people who lived there .
Lamb grew up in the area .
Lamb began his work at the university in 2009 , which has 3,500 students in a city with about 12,000 residents and taught geography and pedagogy .
he received a doctorate in pedagogy in spring .
one of Lambs &apos; longtime girlfriends described him as intelligent , charismatic and funny .
Carla Hairston said she was 15 and Lamm was 20 when they met through shared friends .
she and her friends were in high school , and he was the cool older guy who tried some years to teach her the guitar game .
he was the women &apos;s swarm at the time .
all the girls melted up when he was there , &quot; said Hairston , now 40 and living in the Jackson suburb of Brandon .
Lamb and Prentiss were obviously some time together .
in the emergency call , Lamb said &quot; I killed my wife , &quot; but there was no certificate of a marriage .
they had a dog called Lightning , who lived with them in the brick house , bordering a Bayou in Gautier .
police said the dog was fine .
the ex @-@ husband of Prentiss , Shawn O &apos;Steen , said they were divorced 15 years ago but friends had stayed and had a daughter who was now 19 .
&quot; she was totally destroyed on the ground , &quot; O &apos;Steen said about his daughter .
she and her mother were absolutely best friends .
O &apos;Steen said he never met Lamb , but by his daughter Abigail he heard that Lamb was interested in music and played blues .
Lamb met Prentiss when he and Abigail both joined a summer vintage market three years ago .
they later played together one gig or another .
O &apos;Steen said his daughter writes and sings her own music .
Prentiss was a nurse who worked online for various companies .
Mike Shaffer , a barkeeper and sometimes entertainment coordinator at The Julep Room , a weakly lit bar near Gautier , said he saw Lamb and Prentiss Night on the night of September 5 for the last time after Lamb had finished his guitar and oral harmonic aspiel before an audience .
there was no sign that anything was wrong .
&quot; just a happy couple , &quot; he said .
we were on the cleanup and joked to each other .
I mean , they both had a good sense of jokes .
Schmidt , the dead professor , headed the first @-@ semester seminar program and specialized in American native and colonial history , said Don Allan Mitchell , an English professor at the school .
he was married and had three little children .
he studied at Emporia State University in Kansas and was president of his Brotherhood and the Student Committee .
at the Delta State campus in Cleveland on Tuesday evening , about 900 people , including faculty , staff , students and members of the community attended a candlelight memorial ceremony .
