who smokes has a higher risk of losing teeth
those who smoke do not only harm the lungs , but also the teeth - this suggests a Potsdam long @-@ term study .
the good news : in the event of waiver , the risk drops quickly .
smokers have a significantly increased risk of losing their teeth early .
this is reflected in the long @-@ term study of an international research team , including several staff from the German Institute for Food Research ( DIfE ) in Potsdam .
compared to non @-@ smokers , the risk of losing their teeth prematurely was 2.5- to 3.6 @-@ ounce higher .
scientists had watched more than 23,300 participants .
the main causes of tooth failure are caries and inflammation of the gum , the DIfE stresses .
for these parodontitis , smoking is a risk factor , the authors stress .
the link between smoking and tooth loss is therefore based on more frequent tooth infections in smokers .
it is not clear to what extent smoking also increases the risk of caries .
people who stopped smoking , however , could reduce their risk within a short time , the researchers wrote in the Journal of Dental Research .
however , it could take more than ten years to return to the level of non @-@ smokers , explained Erstautor Thomas Dietrich of the English University of Birmingham .
one has to convince people to become non @-@ smokers , said University Manager Heiner Boeing of the DIfE : &quot; smoking shortens the lifetime . &quot;
not to smoke is good for lungs and vessels and , according to our findings , also leads to good dental health right up to the high age .
in Germany , over 20 percent of the population aged 65 to 74 is affected by toothlessness , the DIfE said .
previous studies have already indicated that smoking increases the risk of early dental failure .
the new long @-@ term study underpins the findings .
archaeologists encounter Kölner Rheinufer on remnants from late ancient times
once again archaeological finds have been made at the right Rhine in Cologne .
near the building site for the new Rhine boulevard , archaeologists at the Roman @-@ German Museum of Skelette and remnants of historic buildings have dug out , museum director Marcus Trier said Tuesday .
since the start of construction on the Rhine , historians have been searching for so @-@ called ground monuments .
for all construction projects in the city of Cologne , the museum is always included as a specialist office for archeological soil conservation .
in the third section of the Rhine boulevards , archaeologists have now been found .
it was already known from text documents that in the 4th century there was a fortress and a church in the 8th century , Trier explained .
in addition to remnants of the fortress and church tower , a cemetery with about 350 graves was discovered , which was probably part of the church .
