Commission proposes new court in dispute over TTIP
to defuse the dispute over the planned TTIP transatlantic free trade agreement , the European Commission has proposed a major reform of the current arbitration system .
the controversial private arbitration institutions for disputes between corporations and states are therefore to be replaced by a more transparent system , which corresponds to far more traditional courts in its functioning .
&quot; we want to establish a system that citizens trust , &quot; said Cecilia Malmström , EU Commissioner responsible .
Swedin intends to include the proposal as a European negotiating position in the free trade talks with the US .
the German government announced support .
TTIP aims to create the world &apos;s largest free trade area with 800 million people .
the plans to reform the current arbitration procedures specifically provide that the EU countries and the US jointly select independent judges for a new investment court .
they will come from the EU , the US and third countries alike .
there is also a second instance for the first time .
it would allow it to appeal against judgments .
so far , the parties to the proceedings have agreed with each other on arbitrators , and there has been no objection to their judgments .
commenting on the debate over the past few months , Commissioner Malmström commented .
in the long term , it intends to work on an international investment court , according to its own information .
disputes between Chinese companies and EU countries could then be resolved .
the investor @-@ state arbitration ( ISDS ) procedure , which was mainly required by large corporations , is considered one of the main reasons for the great opposition in Europe to TTIP .
traditional arbitration courts are criticized by opponents as a kind of parallel justice , over which companies seek damages at the expense of taxpayers , wipe out national laws or enforce a reduction in consumer and environmental standards .
first opinions identified anti @-@ TTIP organisations such as Campact as inadequate to the Commission &apos;s proposals .
it was mainly criticised for not applying the already negotiated free trade agreement with Canada ( CETA ) .
on the other hand , German Minister for Economic Affairs Matthias MACHNIG ( SPD ) described the plans as a major step forward .
the Commission takes into account key elements of the reform drawn up by Federal Minister for Economic Affairs Sigmar Gabriel in the spring with other EU Trade Ministers .
the old system of private arbitrators is off the table .
the French Government also welcomed Malmström &apos;s plans .
the European Business Association BusinessEurope warned that too many new rules would restrict business appeal .
small and medium @-@ sized enterprises in particular could be penalised .
when talks on the TTIP ( Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership ) FTA can be concluded , it remained unclear on Wednesday .
negotiations have been ongoing since mid @-@ 2013 .
however , the issue of investor protection has not been discussed with the US .
initially , a framework for the agreement should be in place at the end of this year .
this date is considered no longer sustainable .
