the BBC &apos;s political correspondent Robin Brant says political differences are also &quot; stacking up &quot; within Labour , according to Mr Corbyn &apos;s remarks on the position on the European Union and limiting profits .
MR Corbyn told the TUC conference that Labour is proposing changes to remove the whole idea of a limitation overall .
hours later , Mr Smith , the shadow labor and pensions minister , said that the party was &quot; very clear &quot; that it was only against the government plans to cut the limit from £ 26,000 to £ 23,000 .
MR Corbyn will be the fifth Labour leader to face David Cameron since he is Tory chief , over the Dispatch box in parliament in the last decade .
the Labour leader , who has promised a different policy approach , says he has &quot; crowd @-@ sourced &quot; ideas for questions to Mr Cameron and has given him more than 30,000 suggestions .
the Islington North MP has said that the Prime Minister &apos;s Question Time is too confrontational , and that he will refrain from both &quot; buzziness &quot; and contending with reluctance and has instead undertaken to focus on serious problems such as poverty , inequality and the challenges facing young people .
MR Corbyn has said that Angela Eagle , the shadow economics minister , will represent him if he does not participate - for example , if Mr Cameron is traveling abroad .
he has also raised the idea that other colleagues occasionally take the floor , and that he raised John Bercow , the speaker of the lower house , to discuss the problem .
when he became leader in 2005 , Mr Cameron said he wanted to move away from politics in the style of a &quot; Kasperle theatre , &quot; often linked to Prime Minister &apos;s Question Time , but a few years later he acknowledged that he had failed to do so .
since it was first broadcast on television in 1990 , Question Time with the Prime Minister was seen as the most important barometer of a leader &apos;s judgment and his leadership in the House of Commons and his position among his fellow MPs , although critics have argued that it has become a caricature and that it needs far @-@ reaching reforms .
