Metcash launches ground resistance campaign to fight aldi-
Metcash is trying to protect IGA stores from an Aldi march in South Australia and Western Australia .
food wholesaler Metcash has launched a ground industry campaign to defend the market share of IGA retailers in South Australia and Western Australia in the run @-@ up to a $ 700 million Aldi invasion .
while Aldi prepares to open two distribution centers and the first 120 stores in South Australia and Western Australia early next year , Metcash and IGA supermarkets strengthen their relationships with local food suppliers and build the IGA brand through mainstream marketing and marketing through the social media , as well as through events such as Adelaide show .
IGA dealers and suppliers are jumping on board , with brands such as ice maker Simmo from Dunsborough , who distributes samples in IGA stores and shopkeepers selling leveraged tickets for the South Australian Football League to loyal customers .
Metcash is expected to release further details of its defense strategy on September 29 , when the wholesaler for food , alcohol and equipment performs its annual investor strategy day .
there is a lot at stake as South Australia and Western Australia account for nearly 30 percent of Metcash &apos;s IGA shopkeepers and generate higher profit margins than Metcash &apos;s IGA network in the eastern states .
buyers in South Australia and Western Australia are notoriously provincial and IGA retailers have a much stronger market share than in New South Wales , Victoria and Queensland - more than 30 percent in South Australia and 24 percent in Western Australia compared to around 14 percent in the East states .
however , analysts such as Morgan Stanley believe Aldi will snap away about five per cent of the food market in these two states 12 months after opening its first markets and will take away all existing players , but mostly self @-@ employed retailers .
according to a report released this week , analyst Tom Kierath of Morgan Stanley estimated that IGA retailers could lose $ 360 million in sales per year and Metcash $ 250 million by the end of 2016 .
this forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 stores in SA and 30 in WA next year , generating sales of $ 500 million and $ 600 million in each market .
the loss in the food and food business and in the quantities on Metcash &apos;s high fixed cost basis could cost Metcash about $ 13 million in profit before interest and taxes , Mr Kierath said .
at the same time , Metcash is losing market share in the eastern states , mainly to Aldi and Coles , although a recent survey by Roy Morgan found that IGA buyers are the most loyal .
Morgan Stanley notes that Metcash &apos;s sales in the food and food business will fall 3.8 percent in 2016 , down 4.1 percent in 2017 and 2.1 percent in 2018 , and will reduce the market share from 14 percent in 2015 to 10.3 percent by 2020 .
last week , leading fund manager Hamish Douglass , the founder of the Magellan Financial Group , told a business lunch in Melbourne that Metcash would likely disappear within a decade .
Metcash declined to respond publicly to Mr Douglass &apos;s comments .
but it is assumed that a board member of Metcash contacted Mr Douglass last week .
IGAS &apos;s market share has fallen from 18 per cent to 14 per cent since 2010 , and revenue from Metcash &apos;s food and food trade , which supplies about 1,200 IGA retailers , has fallen 43 per cent since 2012 , reflecting operating debt reduction at the same time on sales and margins .
however , the wholesaler is wrestling and investing more than $ 150 million to match sales prices with Coles and Woolworths in hundreds of products each week and to improve IGA retailers &apos; ability to improve their stores through fast @-@ growing fresh food and deliver better choice of private label foods .
Metcash &apos;s chief executive , Ian Morrice , says the price adjustments and store remediation programs will come to Elan and hopes the wholesaler will return to profit growth for the first time in four years in 2017 .
Thanasi Kokkinakis is backed by the president of Australian Tennis Association Steve Healy
Thanasi Kokkinakis deserves praise rather than criticism for his behavior .
Thanasi Kokkinakis was one of the &quot; collateral damage &quot; in the recent storm surrounding his friend Nick Kyrgios and , according to the president of Australian tennis federation Steve Healy , deserves praise rather than criticism for his own behaviour .
Kokkinakis , the younger of the talented duo , who is repeatedly referred to as &quot; Special Ks , &quot; got into the spotlight by Kyrgios &apos; infamous clash with Stan Wawrinka at the Montreal Masters .
in a fiery qualifying game in Cincinnati soon after , Kokkinakis and his opponent Ryan Harrison had to be separated twice by the referee , with Harrison calling out : &quot; Wawrinka would have to beat Kyrgios and I should beat the child . &quot;
while he was last seen smashing a tennis bat after a cramp thwarted a potential U.S. Open victory by Richard Gasquet , Kokkinakis was steadfastly defended by Healy .
the teenager is currently in Glasgow , competing with Sam Groth for second place in the singles behind Bernard Tomic in the Davis Cup semi @-@ final against Britain .
&quot; one thing I &apos;m pretty concerned about is the fact that , in my view , Thanasi was dragged a little into the dispute , &quot; Healy said .
he smashed a racket when he lost because of a tie in the U.S. Open , but he &apos;s not the first player to have a racket of frustration with himself , and I know Thanasi well enough to know he &apos;s not proud of it .
but , really , he has behaved extremely well in the U.S. Open , even under the rather provocative circumstances with Harrison and so on , and I think he deserves a lot of recognition .
he has a great team around him , he has a great family around him and I think he has been treated a little too tightly .
he is a very mature 19 @-@ year @-@ old , he works very hard , and he fits into the team and so on , he has never had a problem with the other players , he is respected in the dressing room , he trains hard , he &apos;s good in form , he &apos;s a very stable and mature young guy , and I think he deserves to be judged .
Healy also supported the decision not to consider Kyrgios in the important preliminary decision , which begins on Friday , and he describes the &quot; joint decision &quot; as the right one for everyone , but he secures the man from Canberra as a long @-@ term permanent part of the team . &quot;
&quot; first of all , we want the team to be completely focused on competition and not on all the controversies round &#91; Kyrgios &#93; , &quot; Healy said .
and I think Nick has made the rise very quickly , as people like Federer and Murray have pointed out , rising in the eyes of the public , and he has made some terrible mistakes and deserves all the criticism he gets , but we are trying to support him , we are trying to make him understand the consequences of his actions .
Europe &apos;s refugee crisis : Hungary declares emergency , closes the border , withdraws refugees
Hungary explains the state of emergency and called off the southern border with Serbia on Tuesday , holding all those trying to enter the country illegally , all with the aim of stopping the influx of migrants .
chaos followed the border when hundreds of migrants gathered in a no @-@ man &apos;s land and Serbian officials responded with outrage .
the people who fled violence were stranded for an unknown time in a strip of land on the road between the two control points of the countries and built tents and settled there .
but frustrations rose .
as a police helicopter hovered over them , the migrants &quot; opened the border ! &quot; and cried insults against Hungarian riot police .
some rejected food and water in protest .
Serbia &apos;s foreign minister said it was &quot; unacceptable &quot; for migrants to be sent back from Hungary while more and more arrive from Macedonia and Greece .
( Serbia ) wants to be part of the solution , not collateral damage .
talks must take place with Brussels and other countries in the coming days , &quot; Ivica Dacic said in Prague .
the turmoil on the Hungarian @-@ Serbian border came a day after the 28 @-@ nation bloc failed to agree a common immigration policy at a contentious meeting in Brussels .
however , Ministers agreed to share responsibility for 40,000 people seeking refuge in the overcrowded Italy and Greece , and expressed their hope that an agreement would eventually be reached - next month or by the end of the year - that EU countries would accept another 120,000 refugees , including some from Hungary .
German Chancellor Angela Merkel and Austria on Tuesday called for a special European Union summit to discuss the continent &apos;s immigration crisis .
Hungary , however , did not put its hopes on early action by Brussels or its neighbours .
the state of emergency launched on Tuesday in two southern regions gave authorities more powers to deal with the crisis so they could shut down roads and speed up asylum procedures .
Hungarian Foreign Minister Peter Szijjarto , meanwhile , said his country was also planning to build a barbed wire mine along its border with Romania to stop the influx of migrants through the country - after it ended a fence on the Serbian border .
CBS News correspondent Charlie D &apos;Agata reported that even prison inmates were deployed in the race to create the barbed wire fence between Hungary and Serbia .
in recent months , Hungary has become a major bottleneck for many war refugees from Syria and elsewhere in the Middle East and a point of entry into the European Union .
Prime Minister Viktor Orban , however , has insisted that most of the arrivals are economic refugees looking for a better life , rather than war refugees who are entitled to protection - a view that is strongly at odds with other EU states , including Germany .
the new laws , which came into force at midnight in Hungary , make crossing the border or damage to the 4 @-@ metre ( 13 @-@ foot ) high fence that the government built along the southern border with Serbia , a crime that also imposes higher prison sentences on convicted traffickers .
&quot; because of the situation created by mass migration , the Hungarian government explains the state of emergency , &quot; government spokesman Zoltan Kovacs told reporters in the southern city of Szeged .
we say it very clearly : illegal border crossing is a crime .
Parliament has yet to agree on the deployment of the military , which is expected for next week , but reporters from Associated Press have already seen heavily armed soldiers with vehicles and dogs on the border for days .
Gyorgy Bakondi , land security adviser for Orban , said authorities had 45 people in trying to cross the border , 15 others had already penetrated deeper into the country .
they come up by damaging the fence , they are now in police custody and are accused of committing crimes under the new laws .
authorities are in the process of repairing the fence quickly .
Hungarian officials also closed two of the seven border crossings with Serbia on Tuesday morning after a train wagon with barbed wire to close the borders had arrived .
chaos surrounded the main border crossing near Roszke , Hungary , when Hungary opened a small office in a metal container to process people &apos;s data and pressed a crowd to push back there .
about 20 succeeded , but thousands remained outside .
another group of migrants blocked the main highway link from Serbia and Hungary and said they would refuse food and water until they are allowed to enter Hungary .
election 2016 : Hillary Clinton &apos;s lead ahead of Bernie Sanders in national poll halved
former US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton continues to hold a double @-@ digit lead in the Democratic race for the nomination at national level , but Senator Bernie Sanders is gaining her ground .
Clinton now has the support of 47 percent of Democratic voters in the primaries ( 58 percent earlier ) , while Sanders is second , with 27 percent ( rising 17 percent ) .
Vice President Joe Biden , who has not yet announced whether he is running for president , receives support from 15 percent of Democratic voters of the primaries .
more than five months before the start of the primaries , most Democratic voters say it is too early to say that their opinion is determined by which candidates they will support .
but Clinton &apos;s supporters are more consistent in their election than that of the other candidates .
since the CBS News poll , Clinton has lost to a number of demographic groups , while Sanders has made some gains .
Clinton holds a big lead among women and moderates , but those presenters have diminished .
their support for men has fallen significantly , and Sanders is only 5 points behind here .
Clinton &apos;s advantage among Democratic voters under the age of 50 has evaporated , and she and Sanders are now on equal footing .
Clinton , however , still has a big lead among older voters .
last month , Clinton was ahead of Sanders with a double @-@ digit lead at the Liberals , but Sanders now has a 5 @-@ point lead at that group .
about half of the Democratic voters of the primaries nationwide say they would enthusiastically support Clinton if she were nominated by the party .
a quarter would support them with some reservations and another 15 percent would only support them because they are the candidate .
six per cent would not support them .
perhaps not surprisingly , Clinton &apos;s current supporters are mostly thrilled by her .
the views are more mixed among those who currently do not support Clinton - just about a quarter would enthusiastically support her .
while 48 percent of Democratic voters of the primaries say they support Clinton with enthusiasm , fewer Republican voters say this over their top candidate Donald Trump ( 35 percent ) .
when Clinton &apos;s supporters are asked in an open question why they want her to be the candidate , the most common answer is that she has the right experience ( 16 percent ) , followed by the view that it is time for a woman to become president ( 13 percent ) and that she is the best candidate for the job ( 10 percent ) .
Clinton &apos;s supporters also mention her connection with Bill Clinton ( 9 percent ) .
approval for dealing with the problems and selectivity is also cited .
as the vice president casts a potential for the presidential primary , 57 percent of Democratic voters of the primaries want to see him in the race - although a third believes he should not .
when Democratic voters are asked about who would be their second choice for the party , Biden is at the helm .
of Clinton &apos;s supporters , more than half say Biden would be her second choice far ahead of Sanders .
if Biden chooses not to run for the Democratic nomination , Hillary Clinton &apos;s lead increases before Sanders , from 20 points with Biden in the race to 30 points without him in the race .
fifty @-@ five percent of Democratic voters see Clinton as a candidate with the best chances of winning the election ; but that figure has fallen by 78 percent last month .
Biden is by far a second at this measurement , but the percentage that sees him as the &quot; most electable &quot; has risen .
still , when asked about what is more important to a candidate , Democratic voters call questions about electability .
like last month , not a single Democratic candidate or potential candidate for those voters of the primaries stands as unacceptable .
the Democratic candidates or potential candidates deliver good results on some important features in their party &apos;s primaries .
majorities view Clinton , Sanders and Biden as honest and trustworthy and equipped with strong leadership qualities .
Biden cuts best among the three candidates at honesty , while Clinton &apos;s strength is the lead .
thirty percent of Democratic voters don &apos;t believe Clinton is honest and trustworthy , twice as many say that about Sanders ( 15 percent ) , but 27 percent have no opinion of him on that .
democratic voters of the primaries generally also see Clinton , Sanders and Biden ideologically in line with their views .
for all these measurements , about a quarter of Democratic voters have no opinion of Sanders .
as questions about Hillary Clinton &apos;s use of a personal e @-@ mail address and a server continue to be asked during the term as Secretary of State , most Democratic voters of the primaries are satisfied with their explanation of the matter and say it has not affected their opinions overall .
but it &apos;s a different story in the American public as a whole .
half of Americans are now dissatisfied with their statement , while only about a third are satisfied .
public opinion on this was split in March , shortly after the problem came to light .
most Americans said the e @-@ mail controversy had no impact on their general opinions of Clinton , although 36 percent said their opinion of her had deteriorated .
it &apos;s mainly Republicans , more than six out of 10 , who say their views have gotten worse by Clinton .
although Clinton is seen by her party &apos;s voters as honest and trustworthy , this remains a problem for her among registered voters overall : only 32 percent see her as honest and trustworthy , eight percent less than last month and 15 points less since May .
sixty @-@ six percent of voters do not think they are an honest and trusted person .
at the same time , 55 percent of voters nationwide see Trump as not honest and untrustworthy .
Clinton and Trump , however , get good marks on leadership .
of the six candidates tested , Biden , Carson and Bush perform best in honesty .
a majority see Sanders as more than honest , but as with Carson , many have no opinion of him .
the margin of error for the sample of 351 Democratic voters in the primaries is 6 percentage points .
