that will happen if the Fed raises interest rates
an increase in interest rates comes , and home prices are set to falter , yields on bonds will rise , and the economy will slide into recession .
we know that .
what we do not know is how long it will take and how long it will last .
in particular , history provides little guidance for the economy .
a recession came within just 11 months of the first rate hike and lasted 86 months .
the Federal Reserve &apos;s aggressiveness in raising interest rates is often , if not always , a factor in how the economy and financial assets react .
as a result , US central bank officials have stressed so strongly that investors should not focus on when it begins to raise interest rates , but rather on the period needed for normalization .
in fact , several variables play a role .
in the end , however , market participants may find that the whole excitement of an increase in interest rates has perhaps been exaggerated .
&quot; the first increase in the Fed since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a signal to the end of the era of &quot; cheap money , &quot; Julian Jessop , chief economist at Capital Economics , said in a note to clients .
by contrast , we do not expect the gradual return of US interest rates to normal highs , but still to low levels to lead to the seismic shock that many seem to fear .
however , that does not mean there will be no impact .
here &apos;s a historical trend @-@ based look at how some areas of the economy might respond :
as the market saw last month , anticipating interest rate increases can make things volatile for a while .
once the increase arrives , the influence is not so dramatic .
&quot; there appears to be a tendency for asset yields to be strangled 12 to 24 months after the first increase , which may reflect the delay in monetary policy , &quot; Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study on what happens after interest rate increases in the Fed .
more specifically , in the past 35 years , the market has mostly been in the upward trend - about 14 per cent - on the road to interest rate increases , pretty flat in the 250 days after ( average profit of 2.6 per cent ) , then back to normal state after 500 days , with an average return on the past six cycles of 14.4 per cent , according to a recent analysis firm .
Deutsche Bank said that the impact on the shares tends to occur later in the increases cycle and that returns start to decrease .
recessions are a fact of economic life , but rates often encourage them .
in the current case , the Fed faces some conditions that did not exist before and which could accelerate a recession .
it is extremely remarkable that the gross domestic product will be close to its lowest point in the Fed &apos;s interest rate hike .
according to Deutsche Bank , the 118 interest rate increases since 1950 were only twice nominal GDP below 4.5 percent .
although the second quarter of 2015 was 3.6 percent , few expect this to continue and expect only 1.5 percent for the third quarter , according to the Atlanta Fed .
interest rate increases at such a fragile economic backdrop could be risky and raise the question &quot; whether it is different this time , &quot; Deutsche Bank said .
market participants have taken the whole year on an interest rate hike from the Fed , and all eyes were on the Federal Open Market Committee meeting this week , which ends Thursday .
while many strategists and economists believe the FOMC could approve an increase in that session , futures trading only gives up a 25 percent probability .
&quot; in our study , all the increases have taken place from 1950 to today in a super @-@ cycle with increasing momentum in GDP and pre @-@ recession levels have been coming into the shadows very quickly after the start of the recovery , &quot; the report said .
by contrast , this is a clearly slow recovery from what was the worst recession in the observed period .
the current cycle is by far the longest the Fed has waited since the end of the last recession ; the record was 35 months , and these are 74 months so far .
fixed income was also volatile as the market anticipates an increase in interest rates , and the pattern is pretty similar to that in the capital market .
the main difference is that the impact on bonds is faster than on equities when those change their strategic rate .
for bonds , returns appear to change direction once the first increase / reduction is made in the cycle .
at the end of the increases cycle , bond yields fall immediately , Deutsche Bank said .
Charles Schwab &apos;s strategists believe the rise in interest rates will lead to returns between longer and shorter bonds , leading to a slump in the curve .
high @-@ interest bonds often bring better returns in such a climate , although &quot; we are still cautious about expecting higher yields , &quot; Kathy Jones , Fixed @-@ Income analyst at Schwab , said in an analysis .
what is interesting is that the markets have already adapted to Fed strategy expectations .
&quot; in addition to the strength of the dollar and the decline in inflation expectations , there are some signs that the market has adapted to the prospect of tougher monetary policy , &quot; she wrote .
short @-@ term interest rates have risen , the yield curve is flat , credit packets have expanded and volatility has risen - all characteristics of the market when the Fed tightens its strategy .
by and large , companies that handle the larger portion of their business in the US will benefit as interest rates rise and local products become more attractive .
multinational companies with high debt will be worse off as a rising dollar makes their products more expensive in the global market , as well as financing their debts .
&quot; history shows that &quot; quality &quot; shares tend to respond exceedingly positively three months after an initial rate increase , &quot; Goldman Sachs analysts said in a report for customers .
companies with a strong balance sheet have surpassed an average of 5 percentage points on average after each of the rate increases in 1994 , 1999 and 2004 .
companies with high capital returns and low volatility in their shares also exceeded their low @-@ quality counterparts by an average of 4 ( percentage points ) and 3 ( percentage points ) .
debt will be a big problem .
companies with a high share of flexible interest rates will lose the most , Goldman said .
outside of pure stock games , consumers will also benefit from the rising dollar .
savers could see gains through higher yields , even if experts disagree on how quickly this will take place .
