Internet sales rose the slowest in August and Black Friday may be responsible for this
in the first three months of 2015 , there was seven per cent increase in online sales .
last month there was the lowest result since records began in 2000
online sales increased three years ago by using mobile phones to shop
experts believe Black Friday slowed spending in November
for over a decade , virtual shopping has boomed , and many of Britain &apos;s main shopping streets have turned into ghost cities .
but experts say there are now signs that online sales are stagnating after new figures showed only seven per cent in the first three months of 2015 .
total spending for August represented the lowest increase in growth since records began in 2000 , with only five per cent increase over the previous year .
experts say there are signs that online sales are stagnating after new figures showed just seven per cent growth in the first three months of 2015
&quot; if you look at growth rates for the previous years and go back to 2000 , that has always evolved over time , &quot; Andy Mulcahy , editor of the IMRG sales index told the Guardian .
he explained that online sales intensified three years ago when buyers began making purchases with their mobile phones .
it meant more people could shop online and that people could do so in different environments , for example at home on the sofa .
but now this is commonplace , and we may see growth diminishing .
the black @-@ Friday phenomenon imported from America is cited as a reason for the waning turnovers .
experts believe buyers will withhold their purchases before this event , which takes place last Friday in November .
last year , five times the average number of buyers screamed around their computers to make their bargains , and some dealer websites crashed .
experts believe Black Friday , at which buyers battled for bargains , could stop buyers from making purchases .
a study by the British Retail Consortium found that of £ 5 spent slightly more than £ 1 online .
for some products such as TV and washing machines , more than a third of purchases are now carried out via web shops .
at the same time , more than a quarter of people buy clothes and shoes online instead of in the fashion chains in the inner cities .
