experts criticize report by Public Health England on e @-@ cigarettes
claims by a government @-@ funded agency that e @-@ cigarettes are less harmful than smoking arose from a meeting of 12 people , in part with links to the tobacco industry , researchers said .
experts writing in the British Medical Journal ( BMJ ) joined Lancet by criticizing the evidence used by Public Health England ( phe ) in its report on e @-@ cigarettes .
phe published the &quot; principle report &quot; last month , describing it as a &quot; comprehensive review of the evidence . &quot;
but some researchers questioned the resilience of the data and pointed to the links between some experts and the tobacco industry .
an editorial in the medical journal Lancet last month attacked the &quot; extraordinarily windy basis &quot; on which phe justified its main conclusion .
two other researchers write in BMJ and asked if the claims &quot; build on stone or sand . &quot;
Martin McKee , professor of European Public Health at the London School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine and Simon Capewell , professor of Clinical Epidemiology at the University of Liverpool , said : &quot; a fundamental principle of public health is that strategies should be based on evidence of effectiveness . &quot;
they said the public expects that phe &apos;s assertion that &quot; the current best estimate is that e @-@ cigarettes are about 95 % less harmful than smoking &quot; based on a detailed review of the evidence and modeling .
in fact , this statement comes from a single meeting of 12 people convened to develop a model for a multiple criteria decision @-@ making analysis ( Multi @-@ Criteria Decision Analysis - MCDA ) to lead their opinions on the damage from various nicotine @-@ containing products to a synthesis ; the results of the meeting were summarised in a research report .
McKee and Capewell said that a sponsor of the meeting was a company called EuroSwiss Health , whose managing director had previously received funds from British American Tobacco ( BAT ) for an independent study .
he also signed BAT &apos;s references to public health in a sustainability report , they said .
one of the 12 participants at the meeting agreed to receive funds from an e @-@ cigarette manufacturer , but did not add to the funding he was supposed to receive , according to reports earlier by tobacco company Philip Morris International .
the reasons for selecting members of the panel are not delivered , but these include several well @-@ known e @-@ cigarette champions , some of whom also specify industry funding in the paper .
some other participants at this meeting are not known for their know @-@ how in tobacco control .
the meeting also included the tobacco management of phe .
the group &apos;s research work &quot; admits tellingly &quot; that there is a lack of &quot; hard evidence of the damage to most products on most criteria , &quot; McKee and Capewell wrote .
however , none of these links or restrictions are discussed in the phe report .
McKee and Capewell said that phe &apos;s claims that &quot; there has been no evidence so far that e @-@ cigarettes were &quot; premature as a way to smoke for children or non @-@ smokers . &quot;
prof Kevin Fenton , director of health and well @-@ being at phe , said that response to BMJ &apos;s claims had already been made .
he said : &quot; e @-@ cigarettes are much less harmful than smoking . &quot;
every second life smoker dies from his addiction .
all the evidence suggests that e @-@ cigarettes &apos; health risks are low compared to that , but that we continue to study the long @-@ term impact .
phe has a clear duty to inform the public about what is evidence and what is not , especially when there is so much public confusion about the relative dangers compared to tobacco .
nearly 80,000 people die each year from a disease related to smoking , and smoking costs the National Health System £ 2bn a year .
by clearly presenting current evidence that e @-@ cigarettes are not without risk , but only a fraction of the damage caused by smoking are our national competence .
BBC should abandon EastEnders , says former head of Channel 4
the former chairman of Channel 4 , Luke Johnson , has said the BBC should stop sending programs like EastEnders and The Voice , saying that commercial rivals would &quot; give their right arm &quot; for hit shows like the Albert Square Soap .
Johnson said the radio fee should only be used to make the kind of programs not sent through other UK channels .
he criticized the BBC for placing public @-@ sector programs likely to be seen by a smaller audience in hard @-@ fought time windows against the most popular shows of their rivals and by broadcasters like BBC4 .
after the BBC &apos;s director @-@ general , Tony Hall , said the company wanted to do more in partnership with other organizations , Johnson said he tried six years in his time at Channel 4 without success to get in touch with the BBC .
&quot; I have problems with the idea that BBC programs are commissioned or broadcast , which would also clearly be shown by unsubsidized rivals , &quot; Johnson told the House Communications Committee as part of his investigation into the future of the BBC .
if you want to keep the broadcasting fee , which I do not think is a good idea in the medium or long term , you should at least place your production on programmes that others do not make or commission .
they send The Voice in a first @-@ class window because they want to achieve as much support as possible for their future .
the idea that otherwise no one would show this is a joke , it &apos;s ridiculous , it &apos;s nonsense , of course .
Johnson said : &quot; I don &apos;t see why a regressive tax is funding programs that could also be funded without subsidies .
the Voice is such a program , EastEnders is another , admittedly both own productions .
frankly , other channels would give their right arm for it .
I am trying to see how this should be public television .
I don &apos;t think that would reduce the BBC at all .
Johnson , an entrepreneur for series that directed Channel 4 from 2004 to 2010 , said that the BBC was guilty of hunting for ratings &quot; because of the ambitions of the people working there and because they believe this is the best way to secure long @-@ term support . &quot;
his comments on the BBC &apos;s most popular broadcasts reflect what the former head of Sky , Tony Ball , suggested in his MacTaggart talk in Edinburgh in 2003 that the BBC should sell shows like EastEnders .
Johnson said that the more public @-@ sector niche programs &quot; should go to BBC4 , where you can &apos;t measure pretty much the audience , but they perform their duties , and they can argue that if they go on their apparent holy missions to justify £ 4 billion broadcasting fees , &quot; Well , of course , we &apos;ve created all these obscure programs that no one has seen . &quot;
they put them in a window of opportunity where no one ever wanted to see them .
on the radio charge , Johnson told the committee : &quot; I urge you to find a more regressive system in terms of terms of who can get the best value out of it .
of course , you all think we all think you get a big value here for £ 150 a year , but for people who are a lot of money for the £ 150 , ask me if that &apos;s true , because they don &apos;t consume much of the BBC .
former Sky- and Channel 5 chief executive David Elstein , who also testified before the committee on Tuesday , called for the BBC to review its Reithian mission to &quot; inform , train and entertain . &quot;
he said little of BBC production would now be officially classified as education - he said it was 1 per cent of its TV production and 0.1 per cent on radio - and it should take an example to public television stations in Australia and Canada to &quot; inform , clarify and entertain this . &quot;
on the issue of partnerships , Elstein said the BBC should do more in areas such as that of the Proms , of which he said only a handful are shown on television , and with the commercial broadcasters taking alliances to make everything available online .
&apos;Sonogenetics &apos; can control brain cells by sound waves
the video shows how the Nematodes change the direction at the moment they are aired with sound waves .
scientists have bred worms with genetically modified nervous systems that can be controlled by outbreaks of sound waves .
the tiny nematodes change the direction at the moment they are aired with sound waves that have too high frequencies for human hearing to be heard .
the impulses work by switching motoneuron cells genetically modified to carry the membrane channels that respond to ultrasound waves .
further on this subject : researchers read and write brain activity with light
the researchers said the worms showed the power of a new procedure , called Sonogenetics , where ultrasound can be used to activate a number of brain , heart and muscle cells outside the body .
Sreekanth Chalasani , researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla , California , told the Guardian that one day the procedure could replace the deep @-@ brain stimulation , an invasive procedure that gives electrical impulse into people &apos;s brain to treat symptoms of Parkinson &apos;s disease .
Fadenworms usually do not respond to ultrasound , but Chalasani noted that they did when surrounded by a liquid with microscopic air bubbles .
the bubbles , he found out , amplify ultrasound waves that then penetrate the worms .
the reinforced ultrasonic waves affect structures called TRP @-@ 4 ion channels and found in the membranes by some of the worm cells .
the sound waves cause the opening of these ion channels and activate the cells they are assigned to , according to a report Nature Communications .
to create ultrasound @-@ controlled nematodes , Chalasani genetically changed worms so some of its motoneurons carry TRP @-@ 4 ion channels .
when it applies ultrasound to the modified creatures , the sound waves are reinforced by the microwaves and transferred to the worms where they switch the modified motoneurons .
the procedure has some similarities with Optogenetics , a groundbreaking tool that allows scientists to turn neurons into and out with impulses of light .
but Chalasani said Sonogenetics could have some advantages over this technique .
unlike light , which has to be lowered to the desired spot in the brain at an optical fiber , low @-@ frequency ultrasonic tissues can pass freely and thus be sent to the brain from above on the skull .
&quot; we believe that with gene therapy and a therapeutic virus it is possible to make the targeted human neurons temporarily vulnerable to the ultrasound signal in a clinical setting for certain neurological treatments , &quot; Chalasani said .
other applications could focus on muscle cells and insulin @-@ producing cells , he added .
