eight golden rules for life in student homes
eleven years ago I moved to a student &apos;s home as a self @-@ forgotten 19 @-@ year @-@ old , still in the faith of Berets and moral relativism , but only now I remember the tense smile of those I annoyed - and to the numerous , long @-@ suffering complaints about others .
most of what I &apos;ve learned can be distilled into eight simple rules .
the entry into student homes ranges from slightly annoying to absolutely terrifying .
it &apos;s tempting to snap : people tell where you get , whether and where you &apos;ve taken Sabbath year , where you &apos;re in terms of Corbyn and why you &apos;re &quot; frankly Marmite neither love nor hate it because in earnest , guys , it &apos;s just a heap extract haha , I &apos;m in my room . &quot;
breathe through .
and help others do the same - put questions and show interest .
it directs the conversation and helps you find out the people you like , unlike those you wouldn &apos;t talk to , even if your eyelashes were on fire and those fire extinguishers .
let people .
people &apos;s rooms are often transformed into drinks receptions , movie night venues and municipal meeting points , but they are also the places where people are moving and putting their underwear on .
related : don &apos;t remember to start at the university with a relationship
introverted receive rough treatment at university .
your room should be a refuge , but many student homes form a space @-@ to @-@ space bump culture that is friendly and social and can lead to lifelong friendship .
that can be the hell for someone trying to recover .
nothing in the culture allows you to say , &quot; I like you , and I want our friendship to go on , but you have to go away so I get the energy I used to interact with you . &quot;
try to feel when a commilitone of conviviality is exhausted - and send it a text message instead of knocking .
speaking of knock : do it .
a guy in my student &apos;s homes had the idea that an unlocked door was an invitation .
he saw some things .
friendship close by baking .
as you start the university at the height of the back mania , the clutching of people &apos;s doors to imagine a plate full of brownies is less strange than the greeting of the 1950 &quot; s &quot; Welcome to the neighborhood , I have some baked ... so , and now please smile , if I ask you a personal question . &quot;
offering homemade treats is a good way to make friendships .
your fellow residents feel obliged to entertain themselves and may end up associating your face with a delicious surprise .
of course , this depends on whether you are a decent baker .
badly missed clumps of flour , sugar and fat lead people to sleep when you knock .
stealing food is a common crime in student homes .
of course , clawing chicken is a theft , but is it taking a drop of milk for your tea , too ?
check this with the dairy owner .
the chances are good that they say they serve themselves , even if they cook inside .
if someone steals your stuff , that &apos;s annoying , and you have my sympathy - but try to do it more evenly than my fellow Members , who added a dishwasher to their milk to punish thieves .
she is now in prison .
they should not make noise that prevents people from sleeping or from working .
it &apos;s not just a matter of being a decent person , but that in the true sense of the saying , you &apos;re among the people sitting in the glass house .
a girl on my hallway asked her neighbors if it makes them something to put Drum &amp; Bass a little quieter , because it was three in the morning and she had an exam in the morning .
they responded with even louder music .
when they finally stopped at 5 a.m. , they kindly left their neighbours to sleep two hours before plunging their own music , closed their door and went to their three @-@ hour exam .
wouldn &apos;t it be romantic if your future spouse happened to be entering the same student home ?
conversely , would it not be baseless for you to hold a co @-@ worker for your future spouse , to run to them , to separate themselves again and then to see them every day , and perhaps to see how they are going to overtake all the common friends ?
of course , the heart goes its own way - but if a hot co @-@ worker is definitely not your future spouse , at least try to talk to your underbelly a little reason .
in the exciting moment you notice that someone has left their keys in his unlocked room , the boundary between an ulk and bullying is finer than it seems .
a good stint is funny , but it takes only moments to become boomerang .
give by hiding a valuable and amusing lesson about security - but never forget someone &apos;s room with toothpaste and shampoo .
close her door , and put her keys in a glass of water , which you then put in the freezer - but tackle her possessions on the ceiling no more than twice .
terraced houses for refugees , single parents , low earners
the real estate entrepreneur Markus Gildner builds terraced houses for people who do not have much money .
so for refugees - but also as a signal : &quot; not only do refugees need housing , but also the single mother and the low @-@ earner . &quot;
&quot; I show how you can still build cheap and good today , &quot; the 44 @-@ year @-@ old says in the interview
thousands of refugees will push into the housing market .
the entrepreneur Markus Gildner believes in knowing how quickly to create affordable housing : he is building up terraced houses for refugees in a project .
Mr Gildner , many refugees will push into the housing market .
what solution do you offer ?
Markus Gildner : mass accommodation in containers or turkeys has no sustainability .
because people remain to a large extent here .
given the flow of refugees , we also need sufficient housing over the next few decades .
a very banal , three @-@ storey terraced house is the solution .
Gildner : a terraced house needs least space .
it facilitates integration .
that &apos;s different from subjecting people into residential blocks .
each of the six houses that are being built in the pilot project consists of three units of residence for four asylum seekers each .
each unit has two bedrooms , a bathroom , a kitchen and a living room .
it may be that many refugees will say it is peace again , I go back .
then the houses can easily be rebuilt according to their needs .
how much are the costs ?
Gildner : the price of 160 square feet of living space per house is 184 000 euros , without a plot .
that is manageable .
six months has passed construction .
that is appropriate .
have construction rules complicated their plans ?
Gildner : I got my project correctly .
in particular , it always makes the looming Damocesque value special construction and the pitch regulation .
grinning .
it is still understated who creates three apartments in a terraced house needs at least three pitches .
only in cities there is no place for this .
and refugees and asylum seekers have no cars .
how did residents respond to their terraced project ?
Gildner : there were those who accused me of creating luxury buildings for asylum seekers .
which is definitely not true .
but don &apos;t you exacerbate competition for affordable housing ?
Gildner : true , we &apos;ve had a construction boom in Germany over the last five years , but built luxury apartments that can barely afford one more .
my project has the message , even ordinary people need housing .
not only refugees , but also the single mother or the low @-@ earner .
I show how we can still build cheap and good today .
that is what we are talking about .
Markus Gildner ( 44 ) studied microsystems technology in Regensburg and initially dealt with environmental analysis .
