FedEx earnings mixed , financial outlook lowered for 2016
FedEx reports disappointing results for the last quarter , and the berth giant cut its profit outlook to a full year due to weaker demand for freight services and higher costs in its ground sports service .
the company also said it plans to hire about 55,000 seasonal workers for the holiday .
at this time last year , FedEx announced that the company wants to hire 50,000 seasonal workers for the holiday season .
the stock fell more than 2.5 percent in premarket trading 45 minutes before the opening on Wednesday .
FedEx Corp. said it earned a profit of between $ 10.40 and $ 10.90 in the fiscal year ending next May , 20 cents less than at the previous forecast .
analysts expected $ 10.84 , according to a survey by FactSet .
the lower outlook comes despite the increase in prices , which averages 4.9 per cent and will be effective on 4 January , despite higher premiums for ground sports from heavy and large packages that will be collected from November .
the company said it still expects earnings to increase compared with the previous year due to cost reduction , higher revenue and because of growth in online trading .
Chairman and CEO Fred Smith said the company &quot; provides solid returns when considering the weaker than expected economic conditions , especially in manufacturing and global trade . &quot;
plans for holiday employment were announced a day later than that of rival UPS , which plans to hire 90,000 to 95,000 additional workers , about the same number as last year .
in the quarter that ended August 31 , FedEx earned $ 692 million , 6 percent more than the previous year .
earnings per share were $ 2.42 per share , just below the $ 2.44 per share forecast by 12 analysts surveyed by Zacks Investment Research .
sales rose 5 percent to $ 12.3 billion .
six of Zacks surveyed analysts expected $ 12.23 billion .
FedEx has seen a decline in international priority shipping in recent years , bringing sales in its unit Express shipments to stagnate .
but the boom in online shopping has boosted results at FedEx Ground .
in the last quarter , sales in ground racing rose 29 percent , but operating earnings were basically flat because of higher costs for larger packages and self @-@ insurance .
the Express unit recorded higher revenues due to higher prices , while earnings fell due to higher labor costs in the cargo business .
in premarket trading , about an hour before the opening , FedEx shares fell $ 3.85 , or 2.5 percent , to $ 150.15 .
on Tuesday , they closed with 11 percent loss for the year and 17 percent below a record high on June 11 .
at its most anticipated meeting in the year , Federal Reserve strategists spend two days this week sitting around a 27 @-@ foot Honduras Mahagoni table to decide whether it is time to raise the ladder for the first time in nearly a decade .
drowning over them at an end to the decorated , two @-@ story sitting room is a mural of the United States .
the card is a reminder that Fed Chairman Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues are expected to put the nation &apos;s economic interests ahead of all other things .
the central bank has a two @-@ fold mandate from Congress : maximizing U.S. employment and prices here to keep steady .
but since the Great Recession , Fed leaders have acknowledged that there is an undefeated third mandate : financial stability .
and that third mandate could be the X factor in a decision that is too narrow to predict it , and it will be announced on Thursday whether the US economy is starved to be defused by the unprecedented incentive by the near @-@ zero short @-@ term interest rate since late 2008 .
although most data from the economy show that it is growing solid , recent turmoil in global financial markets could make already cautious Fed officials anxious to step up that volatility by raising the interest rate on federal bonds - and be it just a quarter of a percentage point .
&quot; obviously , the labor market and inflation will be the most important thing they watch , &quot; said Lindsey M. Piegza , chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus &amp; Co .
&quot; but I think if they were looking for a pretext not to raise the interest rate , the increased uncertainty around the global market is enough justification to continue waiting , &quot; she said .
there is no consensus on what the Fed will do , which in itself inhibits the financial market .
about half of economists surveyed by Bloomberg recently predicted a rate increase this week .
financial markets , however , expect a delay from the Fed , with a key indicator showing only a 30 per cent chance of an increase .
this suggests a fall in the stock market if the Fed increases the rate unless strategists mitigate the blow by promising that another increase is far off .
on Tuesday , the Dow Jones industrial average jumped 228.89 points , or 1.4 % , to 16,599.85 .
the action was triggered by expectations that Fed policy will maintain the rate this week , said John Lonski , chief economist at Moody &apos;s Capital Markets Research Group .
it would be a surprise if the Fed lifted rates at this time , &quot; he said .
if she does , &quot; she would have to go very far in her statement to calm financial markets so they don &apos;t panic . &quot;
other experts argued that a rate hike would reassure financial markets because it would eliminate uncertainty about when the Fed will act .
even a month ago , the Fed seemed on track to increase the rate by 0.25 percentage points this month , the first small step in a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would test the strength of recovery in the US .
Yellen had said in the spring and early summer that despite complaints from liberals that more economic progress would be needed , she expects an increase in the rate .
although job creation slowed in August , the improvement in the labour market this year was solid .
the unemployment rate fell to 5.1 % last month , the lowest in more than seven years and near the level the Fed sees as full employment .
wage increases have shown signs of recovery .
and although inflation was constantly below the annual target of 2 % of the central bank , Fed officials said the main reason was the temporary effect of significantly lower oil prices .
the economy &quot; can handle higher interest rates and needs them because of the tension in the labour market , &quot; said Ian Shepherdson , chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics .
but financial markets around the world poured together late last month after China devalued its currency .
the Dow Jones industrial average fell more than 16 % below its peak in May as investors feared a slowdown in the Chinese economy would cut global growth .
the market has recovered somewhat this month , with the Dow now down nearly 10 % below May &apos;s peak .
for Fed officials , market turmoil affects complex calculation of when to raise interest rates .
&quot; if events in the financial markets and news about the weakness of the Chinese economy had not occurred in the last few weeks , they would attract the reins in this session , &quot; said Stephen D. Oliner , Senior Research Fellow at UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former U.S. Federal Reserve employee .
now he predicts she will wait at least a month to get better grip on the impact .
&quot; there is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy , and there is almost no reliable data describing developments in China , &quot; Oliner said .
the health of the global economy is not one of the Fed &apos;s main concerns , so it should not technically be included in its decision @-@ making process .
but ultimately , the Fed has become the world &apos;s monetary authority .
the central bank &apos;s influence has been huge in recent years .
the mere indication by then @-@ leader Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could &quot; narrow &quot; its monetary expansion triggered confusion around the globe .
in a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined , Fed officials can be expected not only to monitor developments elsewhere , but also to consult with other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy .
their decision @-@ making is &quot; more art than science , &quot; said Zachary Karabell , head of global strategy for the asset management of Envestnet Inc .
Jeffrey Lacker , president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond , VA . , noted this month that &quot; the Fed has a history of overreaction to financial market movements associated with apparently not the economic fundamentals . &quot;
Lacker , voting member of the Federal Open Market Committee , in favour of an increase in interest rates , cited decisions in 1998 / 1999 as an example .
a financial crisis in Asia brought the Fed to lower its interest rate by 0.75 percentage points in three sessions &quot; despite limited recognizable impact on growth in the US , &quot; Lacker said .
a year later , Fed officials reversed those cuts .
the Fed should put aspects of financial stability first only during a severe crisis such as the 2008 market collapse , said Adam S. Posen , former member of the Bank of England &apos;s interest rate fixing committee .
recent turmoil is not coming near that level , he said .
&quot; she certainly doesn &apos;t want to get into the situation in which she is afraid of a rate increase because markets are getting upset , &quot; said Posen , president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics .
the Federal Reserve Act still contains the dual mandate and does not mention financial stability , and until that is changed , I don &apos;t think it should advance time .
