refugees need shelter : study warns of housing gap
the situation in the German housing market is tense .
more and more refugees are also seeking affordable lead .
the pressure on the housing market is growing .
social housing is facing a challenge .
distribution struggles in the German housing market have long begun .
with incoming refugees and job seekers from the EU , more and more people are pushing for a market that is already overloaded in many major cities .
they compete with low @-@ income citizens for the last affordable housing .
in order to meet the demand for affordable housing , 400,000 new units would have to be built every year by 2020 .
this result comes a study on behalf of the &quot; Social Housing Association . &quot;
by comparison , 260,000 units will be completed in Germany this year .
that leaves 140,000 homes missing .
refugees are no longer obliged after the first three months of their stay to live as asylum seekers in an initial accommodation .
many then enter the housing market and line up in the long queues before the rental apartments .
according to the Federal Statistical Office , less than half of all asylum seekers lived for rent last year .
however , the negative development of the housing market is not only due to the rising numbers of refugees .
the study also makes significant failings in the housing policy of recent years .
Germany is wrong with a housing deficit that will grow year @-@ on @-@ year .
currently around 770,000 units were missing in the population areas , Matthias Günther , author of the study , complains .
many professionals therefore lived in large cities in WG rooms .
young adults remained involuntarily in the &quot; Hotel Mama &quot; because of the fuss in the housing market .
in large cities , the number of square metres per head has fallen again for the first time in recent years .
to solve the problem , the Social Housing Alliance proposes a reboot .
new incentives are expected to boost social housing .
for example , the basic tax could be waived and the basic tax on subsidised housing could be suspended on a temporary basis .
moreover , the alliance requires attractive tax deductions .
the state bank KfW refugee programme is already well received by cities and municipalities .
a good week after the launch on Monday night , with 184 million euros , more than half of the approximately 300 million euros available had already been retrieved .
now the project could even be increased .
refugees have free time : Croatia and Slovenia launch corridor
after Hungary there is virtually no more progress , as more and more refugees are choosing the way through Croatia .
Zagreb announces its intention to grant transit over Slovenia to the north without hurdles .
however , the route is dangerous .
Croatia wants to reach agreement with neighbouring Slovenia on the establishment of a refugee corridor .
&quot; I have spoken to the Slovenian Home Secretary and if it is necessary we will organise a corridor , &quot; Croatian Interior Minister Ranko Ostojic said .
Slovenia is between Croatia and Austria and is already part of the Schengen area .
the EU country Croatia is not yet a Schengen country .
following the closure of the Serbian @-@ Hungarian border , hundreds of refugees have broken up to Croatia to enter Western Europe from there .
500 people have come across the border at Tovarnik , Croatian television broadcaster RTL reports .
Hungary closed its border for refugees on the previous day .
new laws that came into force on the same day also make ordinary asylum procedures in Hungary virtually unnecessary .
Croatia wants to let the refugees pass .
Croatian Prime Minister Zoran Milanovic said : &quot; you can go through and we are preparing for this possibility . &quot;
these people are there , they are women , children and men who want to live and achieve something .
however , they are people who did not want to live in Croatia .
the Croatian police picked up the first refugees on Serbia &apos;s border with Croatia .
most came from Syria , Iran and Afghanistan , according to media reports .
they arrived both by bus and by taxi to the Serbian border town of Sid .
immediately after their arrival , they had tried to walk across the green border to Croatia .
the refugees do not encounter border fences on the Croatian @-@ Serbian border .
there are other risks to this : there are still sharp mines from the Yugoslav civil war in the 1990s .
mine cleaners are now expected to quickly create a safe passage .
however , after Hungary closed the border , there are few more refugees .
on Tuesday , police counted 366 recorded people .
shortly before Torture on Monday , it was still 9380 .
the new Hungarian laws constitute an offence to overcome and damage the border zone .
35 criminal proceedings have therefore been initiated in the southern Hungarian border town of Szeged .
convicts face jail sentences of up to five years and deportation from the country .
according to the Immigration Department , a total of 94 asylum applications were accepted on Tuesday in the newly established &quot; transit zones , &quot; of which almost all - 93 - were in the main transition .
among the applicants are 13 families with small children and two older people .
there were 40 refugees there Wednesday morning .
in practice , however , no one has any chance of obtaining asylum in Hungary .
in the Hungarian view , Serbia is a &quot; safe third country . &quot;
the rejected asylum seekers should be deported there .
only a few hundred refugees gathered before the &quot; transit zone &quot; in Röszke .
in Röszke , workers started to clean up .
they gathered the garbage that tens of thousands of people had left on the roadside in recent weeks .
locks were dismantled and one of the reception staff in the border area was rebuilt .
no one wanted to comment on the aim of this restructuring .
Austria still has few refugees after the closure of the border between Serbia and Hungary .
it has also strengthened its border controls .
however , around 20,000 migrants were still in the country , according to government figures .
in Salzburg , about 1400 people are waiting for the trip to Germany .
the train service from there to Germany was stopped in the morning on the orders of German authorities .
in open air , smaller groups of refugees met regularly on foot .
