four @-@ fold increase in intake of suspended drugs by children over the past 4 years
toxic Control Centres in the US report a nearly 400 percent increase in the number of children under 12 who swallow heavily alcoholic hand disinfectants , according to the Georgia Poison Center .
according to Dr. Gaylord Lopez , director of the Georgia Poison Center , the cases of revenue from hand disinfectants in children under the age of 12 who report poison control centers rose from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014 .
&quot; children are increasingly coming to these products , and unfortunately a percentage of them are landing in the emergency , &quot; Lopez told CNN .
he said some children deliberately drink disinfectants while some are doing it to impress their friends or because of a mutation among social media .
videos on YouTube show how young people drink disinfectants only because of a cheap experience .
young people reportedly mixed disinfectants with alcohol @-@ containing oral water to get a harder drink .
younger children can be attracted by attractive scents of disinfectants .
&quot; a child doesn &apos;t think this is bad for it , &quot; Lopez said .
many of the more attractive ( hand disinfectants ) are those that are perfumed .
there are disinfectant drugs with strawberry , grapes and orange fragrances that are very appealing to children .
suspended infections contain somewhere between 45 and 95 percent alcohol .
especially for infants , few syringes can lead to alcohol poisoning .
&quot; it &apos;s highly concentrated alcohol , &quot; Dr. Stephen Thornton , medical director of the Giftnotcall Center at the University of Kansas , told CNN 4 in Kansa City .
so , you wouldn &apos;t let a sip of whisky around , but people leave this hand disinfectant within reach of children , and when children come to it , it &apos;s a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol .
Nhaijah Russell , a six @-@ year @-@ old girl who had recently taken four syringes from after strawberry fragrant suspended infection at school , was taken into an emergency reception for treatment .
her blood alcohol concentration was 179 , twice higher than the threshold legally considered drunk in an adult , said Dr. Chris Ritchey , an emergency medical doctor who treated her at Gwinnett Medical Center outside Atlanta .
Nhaijah lent her words and was unable to go when she arrived in the emergency room .
doctors monitored them overnight at a separate child &apos;s hospital on signs of brain trauma as the girl had fallen through the alcohol and had encountered her head , Ritchey said .
&quot; it was very scary , &quot; Ortoria Scott , Nhaijahs mother , told CNN .
it could have been fatal for my child .
Lopez has advised parents and teachers to use alcohol @-@ free products or disinfectants and store suspended infections outside the child &apos;s reach .
beyond alcohol poisoning , some disinfectants were linked to deaths .
in 2013 , two women died in Ontario women following the swallowing of suspended infection , which included a toxic , undeclared ingredient .
health officials suspect the product contained methanol , a deadly solution , rather than ethyl alcohol , which was noted as an active ingredient .
in January , three students of fourth grade in the state of New York planned to poison their &quot; common &quot; teacher by issuing antibacterial products around the classroom , &quot; a police report reports .
the teacher is highly allergic to suspended infection and served her out of her room .
police viewed the failed plan as a &quot; garbage &quot; and referred disciplinary action to the school authority .
