JVA Berlin @-@ Tegel : five square feet of cell are inhumane
the Federal Constitutional Court has given right to an ex @-@ detainee of Justice Tegel , who was housed in one too small cell for months .
because of the violation of their human dignity , prisoners are in principle entitled to financial compensation when housed in too small cells .
that was decided by the Federal Constitutional Court in a decision released Wednesday .
according to the judges , those affected can hope for money even if they were locked in too narrow rooms only a few days ( Az . : 1 BvR 1127 / 14 ) .
in this way , an ex @-@ detainee was successful with his constitutional complaint in Karlsruhe : he was housed in a single cell with around five square feet of floor space in the Justice Department of Berlin @-@ Tegel between June and November 2009 ; the toilet was not separated from space .
after that , the man , who is now at large again , according to his lawyer , had been moved to a larger cell .
his arrest was breached because of the indecent conditions of imprisonment against the Land of Berlin .
but the Constitutional Court lifted the ruling of the Chamber Court of Berlin and dismissed the case for re @-@ examination .
they see the man &apos;s human dignity violated .
Chamber Court now decides on the level of compensation
even if , for legal reasons , only a few days of liability for compensation are valid from the period in question , it was said .
otherwise , &quot; a mutilation of the legal protection of personality &quot; would be to be feared .
the Chamber Court must now clarify the level of compensation .
the constitutional judges have often strengthened the rights of prisoners in the past .
so they only spoke to a detainee in April for damages because he was naked in a cell .
according to a 2011 decision , the multiple occupancy of a cell without separate toilet is also inhumane .
in addition , Karlsruhe confirmed on Wednesday the Berlin Constitutional Court , which in a parallel case in November 2009 certified a decent accommodation for a prisoner .
the then plaintiff was housed over three months a day between 15 and 21 hours a day in a similar cell as in the Karlovy Vary case .
Berlin prisons have also been in the headlines in recent weeks because of a lack of staff .
prisoners are therefore always included for 23 hours , aggressiveness is rising , even to thugs , because of the tense situation .
according to the Justice Department , 21 posts in Tegel are not filled for lack of progress and 19 are to be dropped in 2016 .
Angela Merkel and Refugee Policy : &quot; we create this &quot;
immigration of refugees is a huge challenge - the Chancellor is determined to accept it .
what happens to Germany ?
some 800 000 asylum seekers will come to Germany this year according to forecasts from the Federal Ministry of the Interior , according to Vice @-@ Chancellor Sigmar Gabriel ( SPD ) , Germany is even able to accommodate one million refugees .
Chancellor Angela Merkel ( CDU ) has demonstrated determination in the face of the unusual challenge : &quot; I say again and again : we can create that and we create it . &quot;
the following overview is given to Germany .
according to different forecasts , between 350,000 ( the Federal Ministry of Agriculture &apos;s estimate ) and 400,000 ( the Pestel Institute &apos;s estimate ) homes are needed annually - the next five years .
this is almost twice as much as is being built so far ( 250,000 homes ) .
the lack of housing , however , is dramatic , especially in the case of affordable rental properties : 60 000 to 80 000 social housing each year will be excluded from rental price fixing and refugees will apply for these particularly favourable housing .
Federal Minister for Agriculture Barbara Hendricks ( SPD ) therefore wants to double the funding , from 518 million currently to one billion euros .
far too little is this from the point of view of the Pestel Institute : 80 000 social housing would have to be created every year and the federal government would have to invest 6.4 billion per year in this respect .
scientists and federal government ministers agree that there must also be more tax advantages for investment in housing .
the Institute for Employment and Vocational Research estimates that 55 % of poultry in Germany can be employed in the long term .
however , the refugees in Germany would not be systematically asked for their qualifications to help them enter , criticising Claudia Walter , project manager for integration and education in the Bertelsmann Foundation .
however , it is crucial for the integration of refugees whether they find work in Germany .
work is the key to social contacts , for appreciation in the reception society , but also for the self @-@ esteem of immigrants , says migration researcher Dietrich Thränhardt .
in Germany , according to Thränhardt , there has been a political change : from the ban on the work of refugees to the recognition of work .
while there used to be a ban on the employment of asylum seekers of up to five years , it was reduced to three months in November 2014 , as was the residence requirement , which limits asylum seekers to a place of residence .
in society , a majority of people , including the shortage of skilled workers , have taken the view that refugees should be given access to the labour market more quickly .
a major obstacle to access to the labour market is a lack of German knowledge .
there has not yet been a sufficient range of general and professional language courses .
research also shows that jobs are most often taught through personal contacts .
the creation of networks is therefore , in the view of Thränhardt , the premier route to labour integration .
the Berlin School Administration has found that few fled parents give their children to the Kitas , an estimated 10 to 15 percent : &quot; for the uprooted parents , it &apos;s only very important to keep the family together , &quot; says Ilja Koschembar , spokesman for youth and family in the Berlin Senate administration .
to convince the family of the benefits of Kita , the administration distributes paperwork in different languages .
should the need for educators rise sharply by the large number of refugees , the Berlin Senate would try to increase training capacity - by allowing more specialist schools .
in the countries , students without knowledge of German will be prepared for the lessons .
however , they are not always taught by fully trained teachers , but also , as in Berlin , by teachers who have only one qualification in German as a second language .
there is no shortage of them , says Beate Stoffers from the Berlin School Administration .
the German student works estimate that about 20 percent of the refugees want to study in Germany .
in principle , no federal state prohibits asylum seekers or patient studies - the only exception so far was Berlin , interior senator Frank Henkel ( CDU ) has now abandoned his stance .
student @-@ assisted refugees could be facilitated access to college .
because refugees with a residency allowance or dulling no longer receive benefits under the Asylum Protection Act when they start studying .
the latter do not receive a Bafög in principle , since they do not fall under the circle of the bafiosity .
patient refugees have had to have lived in Germany for four years to be eligible for Bafög , from 1 January 2016 , this margin is reduced to 15 months .
however , this funding gap must also be closed , demanding Steffen Krach , Berlin &apos;s Secretary of State for Science , and the German Student Works Agency .
students should get Bafög immediately .
Islam will play a more important role in the future , because many refugees are Muslims , and for many religion is an important part of their identity .
the state should give Islam the same rights as the churches , and develop the existing state church law into a new state @-@ religious relationship .
it would also be important to set up an Islamic Welfare Association , which deals professionally with the newcomers .
rights also include duties .
for example , Islam &apos;s representatives must agree on clear contact points and be prepared to cooperate with the state in many areas and to give it some control .
this includes a willingness to take heed of religious fundamentalism .
the Chairman of the Central Council of Muslims , Aiman Mazyek , expressed concern on Thursday that religious conflicts could also be entered into Germany .
those who wanted to overcome such conflicts in Germany &quot; immediately have their right to stay here , in Germany , &quot; he said on Bayran radio .
he suggested translating the basic law to Arabic .
integration will be much more than it is today .
this will also have to change the majority society , reducing discrimination and racism will become more pressing .
Germany , as a result of European decisions , has for a short decade an anti @-@ discrimination body and a general equality law .
but it learns very slowly , as the NSU murder series showed , in which police and authorities systematically ignored the racist motive .
equal opportunities for all : what migrant organisations and the interest groups of non @-@ white Germans have been demanding for a long time , and what international agreements such as the anti @-@ racism convention impose on Germany , must become a reality in the coming years if the country is to remain peaceful and use its new citizens &apos; opportunities - for the benefit of all .
in general , Germany is able to provide medical assistance to the refugees expected to date , according to medical President Frank Ulrich Montgomery .
&quot; as far as man- power and capacity is concerned , we are creating that , &quot; he told the daytime crowd .
however , additional money has to go into the system .
to avoid bottlenecks , Montgomery is asking all residents to hand out health cards immediately when registering .
services delivered could later be settled with the federal states .
and , in the long term , it is highly questionable to divide so many people with the limited range of services provided by the Asylum Protection Agency Act .
otherwise , doctors mainly make language barriers .
so far , the Berlin health scientist Thea Borde has demonstrated , migrants are getting worse informed about their illnesses than other patients .
it is not only in clinics , but also in medical practice that interpretation costs should be borne out .
but it would also help many refugees with more general medical contact points in emergency ambulances .
and with another diagnostic look .
among refugee children , for example , there are significantly more untreated disabilities , and young people are concerned about HIV education .
however , German doctors , in some cases other than those in the disease , are clearly aware of their training , according to Montgomery .
&quot; parasites or tuberculosis are not so difficult to detect , &quot; and as far as the shortage of doctors is concerned , refugees may even see relief in sight .
the Syrians have a highly developed education system , and many refugees are even doctors .
in order to be able to practice , however , they would have to prove their qualifications and perhaps carry out checks again .
at least half of the refugees arriving in Germany are mentally ill , according to the Federal Psychiatric Therapy Council ( BPtK ) estimates : most suffer from post @-@ traumatic stress disorder or depression .
refugee children are particularly vulnerable , explains Dietrich Munz , President of BPtK .
a recent study by TU Munich shows that one in five Syrian refugee children are traumatised in Germany .
those who are ill with post @-@ traumatic stress disorder suffer from , among other things , so @-@ called flashbacks with breathing , dizziness , heart rases and death fears .
other symptoms include sleep and concentration disorders , strong horror and emotional deafness .
to prevent the symptoms from becoming chronic , early treatment is necessary , Munz explained .
so far , however , only four percent of mentally ill refugees receive psychotherapy .
although psychologically ill asylum seekers in social offices can apply for psychotherapy , the treatment usually takes several months .
in addition , in the social departments , most of the staff or doctors who are not trained for mental illness would decide whether or not therapy is necessary .
this often leads to misassessments , says Munz .
mansions invite you to dream
with the new &quot; passion &quot; staging , the Circus Probst draws on the traditions of circus art .
the goal is to draw every age group into the band of fascinating acrobatics , animal dresses and one @-@ time entertainment .
now the Circus Probst invites you to dream into the mansions on the brick wall .
&quot; our passion is circus . &quot;
&quot; I can &apos;t imagine living without my circus family , &quot; says Stephanie Probst , Tierlehrer and Juniorchefin .
&quot; passion &quot; - under this motto is current maneuvering .
for more than 33 years the circus has been in the hands of the Probst family .
the gift to inspire the family is therefore in blood .
