FriendsFest : the comedy show giving us serious lessons about men &apos;s friendships
the lack of similar representations in shows is obvious , especially with regard to how the need for men to open up has now become even more desperate than ever before , as suicide rates among young men prove at a 15 @-@ year high .
in 2013 , it was the main cause of death among men aged 20 to 45 in the UK , and it remains three times more common among men than among women .
in an effort to tackle the problem , the Campaign announced Against Living Miserable ( CALM - campaign against a pathetic life ) in 2015 as the year of the man , with the aim of questioning the culture that prevents men from seeking help when they need it .
friendship is at the heart of the fight to meet this challenge .
a recent study by more than 2,000 high school students with depressed symptoms found that if the suffering had a enough high percentage of friends with &quot; healthy mood , &quot; his chances of recovery doubled .
for those who are not depressed , a circle of mentally healthy friends halved the risks of mental problems .
but of course you have to have friends first so that a friendship can work .
in the age of social media @-@ led communication , with its focus on style about substance , the immediacy of the answer is often more important than meaningful contact .
our digital lives have doubled the need to appear strong , fun and successful , even if in reality isolation dominates .
this superficial success is dominated by what psychologists call extrinsic values ; money , image , social status , all at the expense of intrinsically values - our inner yearning for personal development and friendship that affects our mental health much deeper .
and as a video game inventor and billionaire recently explained , money really can &apos;t buy luck .
the nice thing about Friends was that this focus was put on its head .
each character was defined not by his work , but by his personality , which shines through interaction as a friend .
the humor of Joey and Chandler &apos;s frequent hugs , moments at football gusts in cosy armchairs and the yearning of Ross to Rachel - all of which came from the knowledge that men can definitely relate to it , even if they often hold back , fully explore their feelings .
as one member of the telephone crew explained to me , ... &quot; my audience role for people who feel depressed and are suicidal has really shown me how even the smallest interactions of friends can make a difference . &quot;
the men who contact us often feel unable to talk to friends .
the old saying &quot; I &apos;m right to say &quot; has a huge impact , like the feeling that it is perceived as weakness when talking about problems openly . &quot;
friends is one of the shows that comes to mind when I try to offer longer @-@ term redress mechanisms .
it clearly presents the small moments of men &apos;s friendships .
so much my objective outsider status over the phone may also help people in moments of despair , the long @-@ term support comes from a personal network of family and friends .
and so when you visit Comedy Central FriendsFest this weekend with the completely redesigned backdrop to celebrate the day , why not take your friends to a drink in Central Perk .
or , even better , if you see someone sitting around in Starbucks alone , give him a smile and say hello .
you never know what difference your friendship could make .
friends are sent to Comedy Central from start to finish - the entire 236 episodes - for # FriendsFest
