Rome now has a Martin Luther place
just over 500 years after the Reformation , there is now a Martin Luther Square in Rome .
in the presence of city president Ignazio Marino , a previously nameless place in the park on the Oppio Hill was baptized on the name of the German reformist .
in Piazza Martin Lutero , he is now recognized as a German theologian of Reformation .
the park is located in the middle of old Rome next to the Coliseum .
the name was requested by the working community of evangelical churches in Rome .
Jens @-@ Martin Kruse , pastor of the Evangelical Lutheran community in Rome , recalled on Wednesday that Protestants in the city of popes over centuries as a minority could often live only in secret .
the place symbolises the fact that its tradition of Christian faith is welcome in Rome .
Martin Luther ( 1483 @-@ 1546 ) held a few months in Rome as a young Augustine monster .
he then felt the city was a deserted scapegoat .
his negative impressions should have encouraged him in his later fight against Rome .
Luther then launched the split of the absentee church with his theses against the Ablashandel .
Hammer artist invested three years in personal interpretation of the Bible
Jesus with the ( gilded ) village crone is one of the main works that Otmar Alt painted for his Bible .
Klaus Altepost wrote the introduction and updated Bible texts .
at the beginning was the word ?
no , not at the Otmar @-@ Alt Bible , which has now appeared with magnificent images .
at the beginning was the picture for Otmar Alt , who in 150 motifs formulated his very personal interpretations of biblical stories on paper and canvas .
his &quot; language &quot; with colorful colours and imaginative shapes has been preserved by the 75 @-@ year @-@ old - which is by no means synonymous with &quot; funny &quot; images .
on the contrary , it can be quite bleak to adapt to the issues concerned .
about three years Otmar Alt has worked on his Bible project , for which he has made a subjective artistic selection from the many themes of the book of all books .
cycles have emerged that address issues such as crossroads , pads , bids or fatherhood .
he has spontaneously fascinated several partners : this applies to the Luther publishing house with its theological orientation as well as to the Kettler publishing house with its focus on art books .
and here is the author Klaus Altepost , who has dealt with the respective Bible points on the basis of the painting .
he has interpreted the books selected by Otmar Alt and thus &quot; translated &quot; into current contexts .
these lyrics are like verbal mirrors of Alts painting .
they are embedded between the original Bible citation of Martin Luther and a set of the artist , who formulates his own personal thoughts about the situation .
the jewelry band has golden letters .
so the 75 @-@ year @-@ old allows twice a deep insight into his soul , his emotions .
this is a high level of intimacy .
emotions were ultimately the trigger for the Bible project : Otmar Alt , born in Wernigerode in 1940 and grew up in Berlin , comes from a family that belonged to the strict Protestant ruler Order .
&quot; this is where education happened with the cane , &quot; Otmar Alt recalls .
&quot; I tried to work that up to maybe wear myself back with the Lord Father . &quot;
his second concern is to give more prominence to art in a fast @-@ paced period : &quot; the perception of images today is characterized by reclamation , and that is loud .
symbolism is being pushed out .
artists have a different desire and Wonne to show things .
pictures always have something mysterious and are not decorative .
&quot; in this respect , I &apos;m a dinosaur . &quot;
Otmar Alt wants the viewers to &quot; fall into the pictures , &quot; let them work , discover and feel what power they have : &quot; the image seeks its counterpart . &quot;
Klaus Altepost acknowledged Tuesday at the presentation of the Otmar @-@ Alt Bible in the Otmar @-@ Alt @-@ Foundation , &quot; always &quot; a lover of Otmar Alts art : &quot; I like how he understands life with his pictures . &quot;
old did not pay attention to fully capturing the Bible , but selected the issues important to him , including mysterious ones .
&quot; this was not a collaboration on an equal footing , &quot; Altepost says : &quot; this is about the images , the text only explained , &quot; a picture Bible emerged .
for Hans Möhler of the Luther publishing house , this work is an invitation to &quot; deepen his life and find freedom . &quot;
Otmar Alts pictures speak for Möhler both the ( biblical ) language of love and that of responsibility .
part of the original - paper and quality images - will be presented for the first time in an exhibition which will be opened on 15 November at the Otmar @-@ Alt @-@ Foundation .
