robot cars : government wants lead for Germany
Germany is said to be technological pioneers in changing the car , according to the wishes of the federal government .
the Federal Cabinet on Wednesday approved a strategy paper from the House of Transport Minister Alexander Dobrindt ( CSU ) , which includes investments in the development of digital infrastructure .
Dobrindt spoke on Wednesday in Frankfurt on the edge of the IAA auto show about a &quot; new mobility age . &quot;
automated and networked driving will increase traffic safety and provide less congestion , Dobrindt said .
he also wants to discuss the issue with his counterparts from the G7 countries , who are also meeting industry representatives at the IAA .
the transport ministry &apos;s strategy paper stresses , among other things , the importance of mobile broadband and a rapid shift to digital radio .
in order to test new technology , a test track is currently being created on Highway 9 in Bavaria .
in order to ensure that the driver &quot; does not incur additional liability risks , &quot; the Federal Government intends to review the legal framework &quot; and , where necessary , adapt to the new developments . &quot;
for example , Germany wants to work internationally to increase the maximum permitted speed for self @-@ driving cars from 10 to 130 kilometres .
the Federal Government also wants to promote a change to the Vienna Convention , which so far only provides for people as drivers .
in automated driving , the car is increasingly taking the lead , the driver becomes more and more passenger .
the technology is mainly based on sensors and cameras that capture the environment and process data in seconds .
according to a study presented by the Ministry of Economy , highly automated driving on motorways will be technically possible by 2020 .
still , driveless vehicles on public roads &quot; are only to be expected well after 2020 . &quot;
the value added in the field of driver assistance systems and highly automated driving functions at Germany &apos;s location estimate the study &apos;s authors for 2025 to around 8.4 billion euros .
&quot; digital networking of the pin can lead to greater safety and efficiency in road transport , &quot; said SPD transport politician Sören Bartol .
however , the question of liability for accidents and the safety of drivers &apos; personal data must be clearly clarified .
yet Germans still see self @-@ driving cars skeptical - much more than French or American .
a survey by the Forsa Institute on Wednesday on behalf of the audit firm Dekra concludes that only eight per cent of Germans believe that autonom @-@ driven cars will prevail over the next decade , 32 per cent expect only in 20 years , 31 per cent do not believe it at all .
in France , 21 percent of respondents expect autonom @-@ driven cars by 2025 , 33 percent in the US .
in any case , drivers in Germany are not yet ready to rely entirely on a self @-@ driving vehicle .
according to a survey by the digital association Bitkom , only seven percent would agree to give control throughout the journey on all roads .
on the highway , that could still be 15 percent in flowing traffic , 45 percent in congestion .
well every fourth would leave the car under no circumstances .
