jewelry instead of Gardine - Plauener tip as fashion niche
it used to be the long nitrogen machines in and around Plauen to make yards .
the embroidered fabrics and lace were created in large quantities for customers who , for example , continued to work on blankets and curtains .
this is no longer working today , explains Andreas Reinhardt , managing director of Modespitze Plauen .
instead , fashion is important again .
in the early days of the Plauener tip , fashion played a bigger role , then was pushed out by the home textile industry - and is now rediscovered as a niche .
Reinhardt gives some examples : top in jewellery , accessories such as bags and regional costumes .
at all , the so @-@ called vintage fashion , which opposes past bulletins , is a growing order potential .
anyone who does not use niches in the textile industry in Germany is no longer on the market .
we already make up half of all orders .
Modespitze Plauen , along with nine other companies , is a member of the industry association Plauener Top and Stickerei .
only they are allowed to wear the protected label .
in the past 15 years , about 80 percent of sales have broken away .
private specialty stores and wholesale trade are almost no longer available .
our products hardly reach customers by this way .
the bulk goods are now produced much cheaper in Asia and are distributed almost exclusively through chains .
moreover , exports are weakening , currently to Russia and the US .
so there are enough reasons for new ways .
the industry association is also trying to score by environmental awareness , as Cordula Bauer explains from the Stickperle in Falkenstein : &quot; since this year we have been leading a quality label that shows that we produce environmentally and socially tolerated . &quot;
Reinhardt added : &quot; this also refers to the materials used . &quot;
diploma designer Ute Schmidt teaches at the Schneeberger Ausstelle of the Westsächsische Hochschule Zwickau - at the Faculty of Applied Arts - and specializes in embroidery and tips .
in order to counter competition from the Asian region , we need to find high @-@ quality and innovative products .
that takes time and courage .
there is a tension between the designer &apos;s freshest ideas and the businesses that need to think primarily economically , &quot; Schmidt says .
therefore , an existing design is often only slightly varied to keep a customer base .
a few years ago , textile designer Kati Reuter revived the historic snow tip .
in some places , the machine stifles small kitchens .
the Plauener Goldschmiedemeister Bianca Hallebach @-@ Kraucht was inspired by this : &quot; before that I couldn &apos;t start with traditional Plauener tip . &quot;
now she uses the snow tip for her jewelry .
in an elaborate procedure , it shapes the pattern in silver .
&quot; a lot of people in the region identify with the issue of Plauener tip - young and old , &quot; Reuter says .
it also supplies to the US , Australia and Finland - especially to customers whose ancestors have lived in Plauen and surroundings and who want a memorial .
I see my jewelry as a modern ambassador of the Plauener tip .
